The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
peerCertificates = new CertificateChainCleaner(trustRootIndex).clean(peerCertificates);
Set<ByteString> pins = findMatchingPins(hostname);
if (pins == null) return;
```
Reason:
The unnecessary cleaning of `peerCertificates` occurs before checking if there are any pins to validate against. This leads to inefficiencies because the cleaning process is executed even when pinning is not being utilized, which can cause performance issues.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
if (pins == null) return;
if (trustRootIndex != null) {
    peerCertificates = new CertificateChainCleaner(trustRootIndex).clean(peerCertificates);
}
```
Reason:
The fix moves the cleaning of `peerCertificates` to occur only after confirming that there are pins to check against. This ensures that the cleaning process is only executed when necessary, thus improving performance and avoiding unnecessary operations when certificate pinning is not being used.

